Part 1: Data Exploration (EDA):¶

Introduction: In this lab, the activity will examine the relationship between Body Mass Index and diabetes progression using the Diabetes dataset from scikit-learn. The dataset is split into training (75%), validation (10%), and test (15%) sets. The lab will fit polynomial regression models of various degrees with differnt feature to predict disease progression. Finally evaluating model on all sets to assess the effectiveness of each polynomial degree.

Source:Diabetes dataset

Part 2 : Modeling¶

In [49]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error


X_train_bmi = X_train[['bmi']]
X_val_bmi = X_val[['bmi']]
X_test_bmi = X_test[['bmi']]
y_train_bmi = y_train
y_val_bmi = y_val
y_test_bmi = y_test

models = {}



for degree in range(6):

    poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=degree)
    X_train_poly = poly.fit_transform(X_train_bmi)
    model = LinearRegression()
    model.fit(X_train_poly, y_train_bmi)
    models[degree] = model
    y_train_pred = model.predict(X_train_poly)

Evaluation

In [50]:
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score, mean_absolute_error


results = []


for degree, model in models.items():
    poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=degree)


    X_train_poly = poly.fit_transform(X_train_bmi)
    X_val_poly = poly.transform(X_val_bmi)


    y_train_pred = model.predict(X_train_poly)
    y_val_pred = model.predict(X_val_poly)


    train_r2 = r2_score(y_train_bmi, y_train_pred)
    val_r2 = r2_score(y_val_bmi, y_val_pred)

    train_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_train_bmi, y_train_pred)
    val_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_val_bmi, y_val_pred)


    train_mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_train_bmi - y_train_pred) / y_train_bmi)) * 100
    val_mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_val_bmi - y_val_pred) / y_val_bmi)) * 100


    results.append({
        'Degree': degree,
        'Train R²': train_r2,
        'Validation R²': val_r2,
        'Train MAE': train_mae,
        'Validation MAE': val_mae,
        'Train MAPE (%)': train_mape,
        'Validation MAPE (%)': val_mape
    })


results_df = pd.DataFrame(results)

print("Polynomial Model Comparison")
print(results_df)


results_df.style.set_caption("Polynomial Model Comparison").format({
    'Train R²': "{:.4f}",
    'Validation R²': "{:.4f}",
    'Train MAE': "{:.2f}",
    'Validation MAE': "{:.2f}",
    'Train MAPE (%)': "{:.2f}",
    'Validation MAPE (%)': "{:.2f}"
})

Conclusions¶

In conclusion, the degree 5 polynomial regression model did best on the training data. While higher-degree models capture complex relationships, they tend to fit the noise in the data, reducing their ability to generalize to unseen data.

There are some overfiting problem associated with the degree 5 model, the model fits the training data too closely, causing poor generalization to validation and test data. And another problem could be using only BMI feature, which limits the model’s ability to capture the full range of factors affecting diabetes progression.

from sklearn.metrics import r2_score, mean_absolute_error
from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np


models = {}


for degree in [3, 5]:
    poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=degree)
    X_train_poly = poly.fit_transform(X_train)

    model = LinearRegression()
    model.fit(X_train_poly, y_train)

    models[degree] = model


results = []


for degree, model in models.items():
    poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=degree)


    X_train_poly = poly.fit_transform(X_train)
    X_val_poly = poly.transform(X_val)


    y_train_pred = model.predict(X_train_poly)
    y_val_pred = model.predict(X_val_poly)


    train_r2 = r2_score(y_train, y_train_pred)
    val_r2 = r2_score(y_val, y_val_pred)

    train_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_train, y_train_pred)
    val_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_val, y_val_pred)

    train_mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_train - y_train_pred) / y_train)) * 100
    val_mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_val - y_val_pred) / y_val)) * 100


    results.append({
        'Degree': degree,
        'Train R²': train_r2,
        'Validation R²': val_r2,
        'Train MAE': train_mae,
        'Validation MAE': val_mae,
        'Train MAPE (%)': train_mape,
        'Validation MAPE (%)': val_mape
    })


results_df = pd.DataFrame(results)


print("Polynomial Model Comparison")
print(results_df)


results_df.style.set_caption("Polynomial Model Comparison").format({
    'Train R²': "{:.4f}",
    'Validation R²': "{:.4f}",
    'Train MAE': "{:.2f}",

})

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt


def plot_actual_vs_predicted(y_actual, y_pred, title):
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    plt.scatter(y_actual, y_pred, color='blue', label='Predicted vs Actual', alpha=0.6)
    plt.plot([y_actual.min(), y_actual.max()], [y_actual.min(), y_actual.max()], color='red', linestyle='--', label='Ideal Fit')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel('Actual Disease Progression')
    plt.ylabel('Predicted Disease Progression')
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()


poly_5 = PolynomialFeatures(degree=5)


X_train_poly = poly_5.fit_transform(X_train)
y_train_pred = models[5].predict(X_train_poly)


X_val_poly = poly_5.transform(X_val)
y_val_pred = models[5].predict(X_val_poly)


X_test_poly = poly_5.transform(X_test)
y_test_pred = models[5].predict(X_test_poly)

plot_actual_vs_predicted(y_train, y_train_pred, 'Degree 5 Polynomial Regression - Train Set')


plot_actual_vs_predicted(y_val, y_val_pred, 'Degree 5 Polynomial Regression - Validation Set')


plot_actual_vs_predicted(y_test, y_test_pred, 'Degree 5 Polynomial Regression - Test Set')
